{"title_page": "People's Progressive Party (The Gambia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Gambian People's Progressive Party\n|native_name = \n|colorcode = #FF69B4\n|logo = People's Progressive Party (Gambia) logo.png\n|leader = [[Omar A. Jallow]]\n|president = \n|chairperson = \n|spokesperson = \n|leader1_name = \n|leader2_name = \n|leader3_name = \n|foundation = 1959\n|dissolution = \n|headquarters = \n|newspaper = \n|youth_wing = \n|membership_year = \n|membership = \n|ideology = [[Third Way]]<br />[[Agrarianism]]\n|position = [[Centrism|Centre]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Derbyshire |first1=J. Denis |last2=Derbyshire |first2=Ian |title=Political Systems Of The World |date=1990 |publisher=Allied Publishers |isbn=9788170233077 |page=115 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DIkWJ3psB2gC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=People%27s+Progressive+Party+Gambia+%22moderate%22&source=bl&ots=tTl8Qu4O2e&sig=ACfU3U2aDp4OZ1_-My5GEn-gsmDCS7iFeQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbzKjS_LPmAhXHrVkKHZAJCrYQ6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=People's%20Progressive%20Party%20Gambia%20%22moderate%22&f=false |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref> to [[Centre-left]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tradebridgeconsultants.com/news/elections/opposition-win-majority-of-seats-in-general-election/ |title=Opposition win majority of seats in General Election |publisher=Trade Bridge Consultants |date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n|seats1_title       = [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]]\n|seats1             = {{Composition bar|{{GmbNA|PPP}}|58|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|international = \n|colors = \n|website = {{url|http://pppgambia.com/}}\n|footnotes = \n|country=the Gambia}}\nThe '''People's Progressive Party''' is a [[political party]] in [[the Gambia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref> It was the dominant ruling party of the House of Representatives and the presidency from 1962 to 1994.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Edie|first=Carlene J.|date=2000-03-01|title=Democracy in The Gambia: Past, Present and Prospects for the Future|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/ad/article/view/22106|journal=Africa Development|volume=25|issue=3|pages=161\u2013198|doi=10.4314/ad.v25i3.22106|issn=0850-3907}}</ref> The president throughout this time period was Dawda Jawara. The People's Progressive Party lost power after the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]], a military coup led by young, junior military officers.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref> The [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction]] (APRC) then became the dominant party of the Gambia.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2019-01-16|title=The Gambia - APRC Congress|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-825x.2019.08624.x|journal=Africa Research Bulletin: Political, Social and Cultural Series|volume=55|issue=12|pages=22116B\u201322116B|doi=10.1111/j.1467-825x.2019.08624.x|issn=0001-9844|via=}}</ref> The People's Progressive Party remains active, but lacking the same level of support it garnered in the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/The-Gambia|title=The Gambia - Government and society|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe party was founded in 1959 as the Protectorate People's Party (PPP) and was later changed to the People's Progressive Party.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref> The party won the 1962 general election, and in October 1963, upon the attainment of self-government, their leader, [[Dawda Jawara]], became [[Prime Minister of the Gambia]].<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Dawda-Kairaba-Jawara|title=Sir Dawda Kairaba Jawara {{!}} Biography & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> With the republican referendum in 1970, Jawara became the first [[President of the Gambia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bellagamba|first=Alice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNrYsgEACAAJ&pg=PA282|title=The Upper Guinea Coast in Global Perspective|publisher=Berghahn Books|year=2016|isbn=|location=|page=282|chapter=Solo Darboe, Former Diamond Dealer: Transnational Connections and Home Politics in the Twentieth-Century Gambia|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe 1981 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt was an attempt to overthrow the incumbent government when the PPP was in power. It was a civilian led coup-attempt with some support from the Gambia Field Force. The death toll is debated, being anywhere from 500 to 1,000 lives lost.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Perfect|first=David|date=March 2008|title=Politics and Society in The Gambia since Independence|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1478-0542.2008.00513.x|journal=History Compass|volume=6|issue=2|pages=426\u2013438|doi=10.1111/j.1478-0542.2008.00513.x|issn=1478-0542}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6ad0164.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Information regarding the political situation in The Gambia from the attempted coup in July 1981 to the present day|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The coup was put down by Senegalese intervention and as a result, Senegal and the Gambia formed the [[Senegambia Confederation]].<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\nThe People's Progressive Party lost political power following the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref> The coup was carried out by military officers in the [[Gambia Armed Forces|Gambian National Army]] (GNA).<ref name=\":22\"/> It was a bloodless coup that managed to overthrow [[Dawda Jawara]].<ref name=\":12\" /> The Gambia was ruled militarily until 1996 when [[Yahya Jammeh]] was elected as president with the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction (APRC)]] as his party.<ref name=\":22\"/> The subsequent [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]] elections brought even more power to the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]], winning 33 out of the 45 seats.<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\nThe People's Progressive Party was banned by the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]] in all subsequent elections; however, it has joined with other opposition parties to form political coalitions.<ref name=\":22\"/> In 2005, the PPP joined the opposition coalition [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development]] (NADD).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4183715.stm|title=Gambia opposition unite to fight|date=2005-01-18|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> Then for the [[2016 Gambian presidential election|2016 presidential election]], PPP joined the [[Coalition 2016]], where [[Adama Barrow]] was declared the coalition's candidate and subsequently won.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gainako.com/gambian-opposition-parties-set-select-single-candidate-december-polls-convention/|title=Gambian Opposition Parties Set to Select a Single Candidate for December polls at a Convention|date=30 October 2016|website=GAINAKO}}</ref> [[Omar A. Jallow]] is the current leader of the People's Progressive Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/563c63374.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Gambia: People's Progressive Party (PPP), including structure and leadership; treatment of members and supporters of the party by authorities (January 2015-September 2015)|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\nThe People's Progressive Party was created by rural populations as a reaction against urban areas exerting control over the political arena post-colonialism.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref>\n\nThe People's Progressive Party's website currently states, \"The PPP believes that a less pervasive and intrusive government as oppose to the current over-centralize and authoritarian regime is necessary in order to release the creative energies of the Gambian people and to encourage wider social, economic, and political inclusion. Our party intends to reduce the power of government and return to grassroots democracy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pppgambia.com/our-mission-vision/|title=Our Mission & Vision|date=2017-04-02|website=People's Progresive Party|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Opposition ==\nThroughout the People's Progressive Party's period in Gambian national spotlight, there were times of growing discontent with the government.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref> Not only did opposition candidates stem from that discontent, but many opposition parties were created to run against the PPP.<ref name=\":04\" />\n\n=== National Convention Party (NCP) ===\nThe [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|National Convention Party (NCP)]] was an opposition party to the PPP launched on September 7, 1975.<ref name=\":22\"/> The leader of the party at the time was [[Sheriff Mustapha Dibba|Sheriff M. Dibba]], the former first Vice-President of the Gambia. After a political scandal, he resigned as Vice-President in 1972 and later founded the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]].<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nThe [[1981 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|1981 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]] was led by a former [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] candidate. Members of the People's Progressive Party suspected that the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] was in support of the coup attempt and subsequently, many members of the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] were arrested.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nIn the 1987 elections, the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] won five seats in the legislature. Though [[Dawda Jawara]] won the presidential election, [[Sheriff Mustapha Dibba|Dibba]], the presidential candidate from the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]], won 28% of the vote. Then in 1992, the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] won six seats in the legislature.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction (APRC) ===\nThe [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction (APRC)]] is a political party formed after the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|1994 coup d'\u00e9tat]]. The ideology that led to the coup was discontent with the PPP; alleged corruption and a lack of economic development over time.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref> The main figure that dominated the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]] was [[Yahya Jammeh]], who became president in 1996 and served until the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/The-Gambia|title=The Gambia - Political change|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Under [[Yahya Jammeh|Jammeh]] and the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]]'s rule, there were numerous reports of human rights abuses and suppression of the media.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Notable members ==\n\n=== Sir Dawda Kairaba Jawara ===\n[[File:Dawda_Jawara_(1979).jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dawda_Jawara_(1979).jpg|thumb|Dawda Jawara, president of the Gambia from 1970 to 1994 and a member of the PPP.]]\n[[Dawda Jawara|Sir Dawda Kairaba Jawara]] served as the leader of the People's Progressive Party from 1959 until 1994 when he was overthrown.<ref name=\":32\"/> He is responsible for changing the name of the party from the Protectorate People's Party to the People's Progressive Party.<ref name=\":32\" /> Before serving as president for [[the Gambia]] he was elected into the legislature in 1960. During this time, he also served as the minister of education. He later became the prime minister of the Gambia in 1962 and was knighted in 1966, following independence.<ref name=\":32\" /> Upon the creation of a new constitution in 1970, Jawara became the president and served until the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the coup, [[Dawda Jawara|Jawara]] was exiled and lived in [[Senegal]] and later [[London]]. He was later given amnesty but was not given the right to participate in the Gambian political arena.<ref name=\":32\" />\n[[null|link=|thumb|[[File:Omar A. Jallow 2017.png|thumb|[[Omar A. Jallow|Omar Jallow]], the current leader of the PPP.]]]]\n\nDawda Jawara died on August 27, 2019 at 95 years old.<ref name=\":32\" />[[File:Omar A. Jallow 2017.png|thumb|[[Omar A. Jallow|Omar Jallow]], the current leader of the PPP.]]\nDawda Jawara died on August 27, 2019 at 95 years old.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\n=== Omar A. Jallow ===\n[[Omar A. Jallow]] is the current leader of the People's Progressive Party. He was a member of [[Dawda Jawara]]'s cabinet up until the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|1994 coup d'\u00e9tat]], when he was arrested. Under the [[Yahya Jammeh|Jammeh]] administration, he was reportedly jailed over 22 times.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN15Y0GR|title=Gambia leader heralds new dawn for minister jailed 22 times|date=2017-02-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Yahya Jammeh|Jammeh]] was not re-elected following the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]], [[Omar A. Jallow|Omar Jallow]] was appointed the minister of agriculture as he was in the [[Dawda Jawara|Jawara]] administration.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Electoral history ==\n\n===Presidential elections===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n!Election\n!Party candidate\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!Result\n|-\n|[[1982 Gambian general election|1982]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Dawda Jawara]]\n|137,020\n|72.44%\n|'''Elected''' {{Y}}\n|-\n|[[1987 Gambian general election|1987]]\n|123,385\n|59.18%\n|'''Elected''' {{Y}}\n|-\n|[[1992 Gambian general election|1992]]\n|117,549\n|58.48%\n|'''Elected''' {{Y}}\n|}\n\n=== National Assembly elections ===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n!Election\n!Votes\n!%\n!'''Seats'''\n!'''+/\u2013'''\n!'''Position'''\n!'''Position'''\n|-\n|[[1960 Gambian legislative election|1960]]\n|25,490\n|36.9%\n|{{Composition bar|9|19|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 9\n|{{increase}} 2nd\n|{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[1962 Gambian legislative election|1962]]\n|56,343\n|57.7%\n|{{Composition bar|18|32|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 9\n|{{increase}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1966 Gambian general election|1966]]\n|81,313\n|65.3%\n|{{Composition bar|24|32|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 6\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1972 Gambian general election|1972]]\n|65,388\n|63.0%\n|{{Composition bar|28|32|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1977 Gambian general election|1977]]\n|123,297\n|69.6%\n|{{Composition bar|29|35|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 1\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1982 Gambian general election|1982]]\n|102,545\n|61.7%\n|{{Composition bar|27|35|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{decrease}} 2\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1987 Gambian general election|1987]]\n|119,248\n|56.4%\n|{{Composition bar|31|36|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1992 Gambian general election|1992]]\n|109,059\n|54.3%\n|{{Composition bar|25|36|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{decrease}} 6\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1997 Gambian parliamentary election|1997]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |Banned\n|{{Composition bar|0|49|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{decrease}} 25\n|\n|{{Color|red|Extra-parliamentary}}\n|-\n|[[2017 Gambian parliamentary election|2017]]\n|9,503\n|2.5%\n|{{Composition bar|2|58|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 2\n|{{increase}} 6th\n|{{color|#FF69B4|PPP}}-[[United Democratic Party (Gambia)|UDP]]-[[National Reconciliation Party|NRP]] {{color|green|coalition}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gambian political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Political parties in the Gambia]]\n[[Category:People's Progressive Party (Gambia) politicians|*Main]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Gambian People's Progressive Party\n|native_name = \n|colorcode = #FF69B4\n|logo = People's Progressive Party (Gambia) logo.png\n|leader = [[Omar A. Jallow]]\n|president = \n|chairperson = \n|spokesperson = \n|leader1_name = \n|leader2_name = \n|leader3_name = \n|foundation = 1959\n|dissolution = \n|headquarters = \n|newspaper = \n|youth_wing = \n|membership_year = \n|membership = \n|ideology = [[Third Way]]<br />[[Agrarianism]]\n|position = [[Centrism|Centre]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Derbyshire |first1=J. Denis |last2=Derbyshire |first2=Ian |title=Political Systems Of The World |date=1990 |publisher=Allied Publishers |isbn=9788170233077 |page=115 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DIkWJ3psB2gC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=People%27s+Progressive+Party+Gambia+%22moderate%22&source=bl&ots=tTl8Qu4O2e&sig=ACfU3U2aDp4OZ1_-My5GEn-gsmDCS7iFeQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbzKjS_LPmAhXHrVkKHZAJCrYQ6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=People's%20Progressive%20Party%20Gambia%20%22moderate%22&f=false |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref> to [[Centre-left]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tradebridgeconsultants.com/news/elections/opposition-win-majority-of-seats-in-general-election/ |title=Opposition win majority of seats in General Election |publisher=Trade Bridge Consultants |date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n|seats1_title       = [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]]\n|seats1             = {{Composition bar|{{GmbNA|PPP}}|58|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|international = \n|colors = \n|website = {{url|http://pppgambia.com/}}\n|footnotes = \n|country=the Gambia}}\nThe '''People's Progressive Party''' is a [[political party]] in [[the Gambia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref> It was the dominant ruling party of the House of Representatives and the presidency from 1962 to 1994.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Edie|first=Carlene J.|date=2000-03-01|title=Democracy in The Gambia: Past, Present and Prospects for the Future|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/ad/article/view/22106|journal=Africa Development|volume=25|issue=3|pages=161\u2013198|doi=10.4314/ad.v25i3.22106|issn=0850-3907}}</ref> The president throughout this time period was Dawda Jawara. The People's Progressive Party lost power after the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]], a military coup led by young, junior military officers.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref> The [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction]] (APRC) then became the dominant party of the Gambia.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2019-01-16|title=The Gambia - APRC Congress|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-825x.2019.08624.x|journal=Africa Research Bulletin: Political, Social and Cultural Series|volume=55|issue=12|pages=22116B\u201322116B|doi=10.1111/j.1467-825x.2019.08624.x|issn=0001-9844|via=}}</ref> The People's Progressive Party remains active, but lacking the same level of support it garnered in the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/The-Gambia|title=The Gambia - Government and society|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe party was founded in 1959 as the Protectorate People's Party (PPP) and was later changed to the People's Progressive Party.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref> The party won the 1962 general election, and in October 1963, upon the attainment of self-government, their leader, [[Dawda Jawara]], became [[Prime Minister of the Gambia]].<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Dawda-Kairaba-Jawara|title=Sir Dawda Kairaba Jawara {{!}} Biography & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> With the republican referendum in 1970, Jawara became the first [[President of the Gambia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bellagamba|first=Alice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNrYsgEACAAJ&pg=PA282|title=The Upper Guinea Coast in Global Perspective|publisher=Berghahn Books|year=2016|isbn=|location=|page=282|chapter=Solo Darboe, Former Diamond Dealer: Transnational Connections and Home Politics in the Twentieth-Century Gambia|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe 1981 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt was an attempt to overthrow the incumbent government when the PPP was in power. It was a civilian led coup-attempt with some support from the Gambia Field Force. The death toll is debated, being anywhere from 500 to 1,000 lives lost.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Perfect|first=David|date=March 2008|title=Politics and Society in The Gambia since Independence|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1478-0542.2008.00513.x|journal=History Compass|volume=6|issue=2|pages=426\u2013438|doi=10.1111/j.1478-0542.2008.00513.x|issn=1478-0542}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6ad0164.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Information regarding the political situation in The Gambia from the attempted coup in July 1981 to the present day|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The coup was put down by Senegalese intervention and as a result, Senegal and the Gambia formed the [[Senegambia Confederation]].<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\nThe People's Progressive Party lost political power following the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref> The coup was carried out by military officers in the [[Gambia Armed Forces|Gambian National Army]] (GNA).<ref name=\":22\"/> It was a bloodless coup that managed to overthrow [[Dawda Jawara]].<ref name=\":12\" /> The Gambia was ruled militarily until 1996 when [[Yahya Jammeh]] was elected as president with the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction (APRC)]] as his party.<ref name=\":22\"/> The subsequent [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]] elections brought even more power to the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]], winning 33 out of the 45 seats.<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\nThe People's Progressive Party was banned by the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]] in all subsequent elections; however, it has joined with other opposition parties to form political coalitions.<ref name=\":22\"/> In 2005, the PPP joined the opposition coalition [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development]] (NADD).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4183715.stm|title=Gambia opposition unite to fight|date=2005-01-18|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> Then for the [[2016 Gambian presidential election|2016 presidential election]], PPP joined the [[Coalition 2016]], where [[Adama Barrow]] was declared the coalition's candidate and subsequently won.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gainako.com/gambian-opposition-parties-set-select-single-candidate-december-polls-convention/|title=Gambian Opposition Parties Set to Select a Single Candidate for December polls at a Convention|date=30 October 2016|website=GAINAKO}}</ref> [[Omar A. Jallow]] is the current leader of the People's Progressive Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/563c63374.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Gambia: People's Progressive Party (PPP), including structure and leadership; treatment of members and supporters of the party by authorities (January 2015-September 2015)|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\nThe People's Progressive Party was created by rural populations as a reaction against urban areas exerting control over the political arena post-colonialism.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref>\n\nThe People's Progressive Party's website currently states, \"The PPP believes that a less pervasive and intrusive government as oppose to the current over-centralize and authoritarian regime is necessary in order to release the creative energies of the Gambian people and to encourage wider social, economic, and political inclusion. Our party intends to reduce the power of government and return to grassroots democracy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pppgambia.com/our-mission-vision/|title=Our Mission & Vision|date=2017-04-02|website=People's Progresive Party|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Opposition ==\nThroughout the People's Progressive Party's period in Gambian national spotlight, there were times of growing discontent with the government.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=Arnold|date=1975|title=From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/484012|journal=Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des \u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=9|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.2307/484012|issn=0008-3968}}</ref> Not only did opposition candidates stem from that discontent, but many opposition parties were created to run against the PPP.<ref name=\":04\" />\n\n=== National Convention Party (NCP) ===\nThe [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|National Convention Party (NCP)]] was an opposition party to the PPP launched on September 7, 1975.<ref name=\":22\"/> The leader of the party at the time was [[Sheriff Mustapha Dibba|Sheriff M. Dibba]], the former first Vice-President of the Gambia. After a political scandal, he resigned as Vice-President in 1972 and later founded the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]].<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nThe [[1981 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|1981 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]] was led by a former [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] candidate. Members of the People's Progressive Party suspected that the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] was in support of the coup attempt and subsequently, many members of the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] were arrested.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nIn the 1987 elections, the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] won five seats in the legislature. Though [[Dawda Jawara]] won the presidential election, [[Sheriff Mustapha Dibba|Dibba]], the presidential candidate from the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]], won 28% of the vote. Then in 1992, the [[National Convention Party (The Gambia)|NCP]] won six seats in the legislature.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction (APRC) ===\nThe [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction (APRC)]] is a political party formed after the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|1994 coup d'\u00e9tat]]. The ideology that led to the coup was discontent with the PPP; alleged corruption and a lack of economic development over time.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref> The main figure that dominated the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]] was [[Yahya Jammeh]], who became president in 1996 and served until the the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/The-Gambia|title=The Gambia - Political change|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Under [[Yahya Jammeh|Jammeh]] and the [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]]'s rule, there were numerous reports of human rights abuses and suppression of the media.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Notable members ==\n\n=== Sir Dawda Kairaba Jawara ===\n[[File:Dawda_Jawara_(1979).jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dawda_Jawara_(1979).jpg|thumb|Dawda Jawara, president of the Gambia from 1970 to 1994 and a member of the PPP.]]\n[[Dawda Jawara|Sir Dawda Kairaba Jawara]] served as the leader of the People's Progressive Party from 1959 until 1994 when he was overthrown.<ref name=\":32\"/> He is responsible for changing the name of the party from the Protectorate People's Party to the People's Progressive Party.<ref name=\":32\" /> Before serving as president for [[the Gambia]] he was elected into the legislature in 1960. During this time, he also served as the minister of education. He later became the prime minister of the Gambia in 1962 and was knighted in 1966, following independence.<ref name=\":32\" /> Upon the creation of a new constitution in 1970, Jawara became the president and served until the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Saine|first=Abdoulaye S.M.|date=October 1996|title=The Coup d'Etat in The Gambia, 1994: The End of the First Republic|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0095327x9602300105|journal=Armed Forces & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=97\u2013111|doi=10.1177/0095327x9602300105|issn=0095-327X}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the coup, [[Dawda Jawara|Jawara]] was exiled and lived in [[Senegal]] and later [[London]]. He was later given amnesty but was not given the right to participate in the Gambian political arena.<ref name=\":32\" />\n[[null|link=|thumb|[[File:Omar A. Jallow 2017.png|thumb|[[Omar A. Jallow|Omar Jallow]], the current leader of the PPP.]]]]\n\nDawda Jawara died on August 27, 2019 at 95 years old.<ref name=\":32\" />[[File:Omar A. Jallow 2017.png|thumb|[[Omar A. Jallow|Omar Jallow]], the current leader of the PPP.]]\nDawda Jawara died on August 27, 2019 at 95 years old.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\n=== Omar A. Jallow ===\n[[Omar A. Jallow]] is the current leader of the People's Progressive Party. He was a member of [[Dawda Jawara]]'s cabinet up until the [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|1994 coup d'\u00e9tat]], when he was arrested. Under the [[Yahya Jammeh|Jammeh]] administration, he was reportedly jailed over 22 times.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gambia-politics-idUSKBN15Y0GR|title=Gambia leader heralds new dawn for minister jailed 22 times|date=2017-02-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Yahya Jammeh|Jammeh]] was not re-elected following the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]], [[Omar A. Jallow|Omar Jallow]] was appointed the minister of agriculture as he was in the [[Dawda Jawara|Jawara]] administration.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Electoral history ==\n\n===Presidential elections===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n!Election\n!Party candidate\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!Result\n|-\n|[[1982 Gambian general election|1982]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Dawda Jawara]]\n|137,020\n|72.44%\n|'''Elected''' {{Y}}\n|-\n|[[1987 Gambian general election|1987]]\n|123,385\n|59.18%\n|'''Elected''' {{Y}}\n|-\n|[[1992 Gambian general election|1992]]\n|117,549\n|58.48%\n|'''Elected''' {{Y}}\n|}\n\n=== National Assembly elections ===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n!Election\n!Votes\n!%\n!'''Seats'''\n!'''+/\u2013'''\n!'''Position'''\n!'''Position'''\n|-\n|[[1960 Gambian legislative election|1960]]\n|25,490\n|36.9%\n|{{Composition bar|9|19|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 9\n|{{increase}} 2nd\n|{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[1962 Gambian legislative election|1962]]\n|56,343\n|57.7%\n|{{Composition bar|18|32|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 9\n|{{increase}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1966 Gambian general election|1966]]\n|81,313\n|65.3%\n|{{Composition bar|24|32|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 6\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1972 Gambian general election|1972]]\n|65,388\n|63.0%\n|{{Composition bar|28|32|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|{{steady}} 1st\n|{{color|green|PPP majority}}\n|-\n|[[1977 Gambian general election|1977]]\n|123,297\n|69.6%\n|{{Composition bar|29|35|hex=#FF69B4}}\n|{{increas